segments.text: Okay, let's go back to where we were.
I guess if I jog my memory, I could find a couple more, but two things I can tell you that you might not hear very often.
One was when we had the search to replace Hubert.
The central administration of Texas A&M, and I mean from the president on down, were absolutely amazed by the quality of
that we had who were interested in the deanship of Texas A&M.
We had the former dean at Ohio State, which was then ranked number two in College of Education nationwide.
And he was one of the grand architects of that who was interested.
We had a couple of other people who were really premier researchers.
One, the president of the International Reading Society.
But the four finalists that we brought to the table
for that, impressed the administration.
Were you on that committee?
Yes.
I'd even go so far that they suggested there wasn't another college then at Texas A&M that could get people from those prestigious universities to apply.
They were just immensely impressed with the people we had.
And it did a lot to help transform the image of the college.
Every college is trying to transform its image in a more positive way.
Was there one thing that put Corrigan above these?
Since they were all such, what finally leaned the committee or the search or whoever towards Corrigan?
What was it about him that stood out above these other fantastics?
I would say it's a very open style.

It just, it was immediately apparent when you met Corrigan, any context in that search, whether it was in the college or over at the president's office, just a real gregarious and amicable and friendly, friendly person.
The other bit, and more important, is that what Corrigan did was give a lecture.
And that lecture centered on equity.
For administration people, there are three big things that we study.
Effectiveness, efficiency, and equity.
In fact, the whole study of administration might be geared around those three anchors.

Corrigan gave a very clear message when he gave his lecture, and it was delivered over in the small theater in Rudder, that he was very much interested in equity, very much interested in students' rights.
very interested in these types of policy issues being central in the activities, not only research, but research, teaching, and service activities of the college.
If he were to be a dean, that would be a concern.
That rallied, I'd say, 30 of the premier folks in the college to start lobbying the entire search committee.
topped over all the way across the table.
Once he came to campus, he was the first choice.
What about Jim McNamara's contribution?
How can we summarize that?
And I know you're a long ways from reaching your peak because you keep...
I'm sure you want to wrap this up, but I want to tell you this one other, because it's a document you need to look at.
And it does have some really good things.
Second thing that really impressed...
The central administration and the teacher education community at large, the national teacher education community, were R ratings on the NK study.
I have that one.
As a matter of fact, three or four of the people who were on the NK team tried to come to Texas A&M.
John Dillard is one of the members on the NK team who was at Texas A&M.
John came from Oklahoma State, the Texas A&M.
He was on the search committee.
We got accolades almost across the board, but the one place where we got accolades that almost no other institution got them... Now, this was on which one?
The 1970, which MCAT?
The most recent MCAT, the last MCAT we had.
It would have to be since 1980, so it's probably in 83 or 82.
Yeah, somewhere around there, in the early 80s.
We got accolades on the long-range planning and program evaluation standard.
That same year, both Purdue and Alabama, which are two large universities, were failed.
And the statistics I looked at before we had the review showed that almost no institutions pick up accolades or highest marks.
When they looked at what we did... Are those in the report?
The marks are in the report itself?
Yeah.
Okay.
We picked up accolades on that standard.
And one of the reasons... Well, I wrote that standard.
It's Standard 6.
You might want to look at that report.
It captures a lot of the inquiry activity.
It captures a lot of the things.
One thing that put us right over the top was that we did an international telephone sample
of our former graduates in the College of Ed, 240 of them, 40 from each of the six departments.
And we asked our graduate students, former graduate students, how can we improve Texas A&M?
And there are seven volumes in that.
I can tell you just this one thing.
You'll see why there's seven volumes.
There were ten, we played the twenty questions game.
There would be ten questions that would be common across all six departments, and then there would be ten questions that would be unique in each department.
So if you summed over any department, they had ten evaluation and planning questions which were unique to them, and they had ten that related to them and to the college as well.
We involved over 120 members in the College of Education doing that study.
We had department heads doing telephone calls.
Now, these are true, random samples of our graduates since 1969, right up to 1982.
And the whole push of that survey was, we respect your professional competence.
Tell us how we can be better.
Tell us what we can do to maintain continuing contacts with y'all.
Where can I find all that?
I'll give you a setup.
All right.
Now, I would say that that's probably one of my best contributions to Texas A&M.
And it was really a turning point in just selling me on the institution.
I've always been sold on it.
I'm up beyond it.
The dean underwrote that study.
The department heads cooperated.
Seven students taking advanced doctoral work with me designed the entire architecture for that study.
And it involved working with 120 people.
And then we reported, yes, about half of those people are faculty and about half are students.
And when that NK commission saw that study, it just put their lights out.
They had never seen anything like that anywhere.
Has there something come out of that that has really made dramatic change in the college?
What was done with all that information, and how was it utilized?
I'm going to say there isn't.
And I think you're going to appreciate my reason why.
Administration, it never links its success to a single thing, to a whole conglomerate of things.
A really cheap analogy might be someone who's running for school board and gets elected.
And then they want to give some advice to someone else.
And they had yard signs and brochures.
Now, which one do you want to give up?
Well, they don't know what to give up.
They just know that when you take the yard signs and the brochures together, they got them elected.
I would say that there were several things since when Corrigan came that were all in that same orbit, inquiry group activity,

the increasing quality in some of the enrollment, the new sense of mission, the study, faculty members who were becoming tenured and seasoned and now didn't have to worry about individual efforts but could be team players.
They were mentoring younger faculty.
I would say all those things taken collectively enhanced the college.
And that all the things were falling into place
for us to make some real quantum leaps.
And I would say that both Hubert and Corrigan are responsible with different leadership styles, different pieces of the pie.
They're all responsible for creating the advocacy and enthusiasm of our faculty.
And is there something, as you look into the future, say the year 2000 and even beyond, where do you think that's going to take us?
What do you think will be the ultimate
What will we reap from all of this leadership and so forth?
Yeah.
I'm worried about where the college is going now.
I think we're not ready to take the big quantum leap it takes to do research.
I've alluded to that in some of my comments.
I think people are burned out in terms of stretching themselves to be involved in other efforts.
And if the college is going to be really somewhere in the year 2000, you must remember the people that brought them.
Now, a good example.
For years, Donna Norton has been, and I would say she's, add her name to the premier list of researchers in the college, if you can go back.
And I'll give you the echo.
Add Donna Norton to the list.
Right.
OK. Donna is now without the money from the Meadows Foundation grant.
And what do they have her doing?
teaching three courses.
The day that the grant's run out, people are back to these.

Now, that doesn't happen in all the departments, but there's a really good example of a researcher who made an enormous contribution with her research on training low-achieving minority students in reading.
And literally took the lowest 5% of the readers in Bryan and made astronomical gains with them.
And now what's she doing?
She's back teaching three courses.
They're giving her a lot more committee assignments.
Do you understand what I'm saying?
Sure.
That's what I'm worried about in the college.
I'm worried that that's not there.
What would be the ideal would be for her to be able to get funding from somewhere else?
Is that what... Well, I think it's like any other R&D effort in a corporation.
If someone's productive for four or five years...
They either need a sabbatical or they need some sort of downtime where they can just sort of reflect on that activity and sort of get their battery run up again.
Is there a sabbatical program in place?
I mean, do people get sabbaticals and stuff?
There's a sabbatical that you can apply to for the university, but we don't have that.
A lot of our people don't want to leave just now.
They're here, and they're smart enough to know that they want their kids to be in a single school system all the way through, at least until they get out of high school.
If you look at our demography, most of our faculty are there, so they don't want to leave.
But they need internal relief, not a sabbatical.
By internal relief, you mean just time to... Yeah, some time to reflect.
They create their own monastic retreat and reflect on what made their immediate past so productive, so useful.
What are its implications?
I don't see the college in a reflective mode.
I don't see it trying to reward people.
We've hit a plateau of success.
I've heard that word already twice today, that we are in a plateau.
Do you see your role within the college changing at all in the near future?
Will your focus still be maintained where you are now?
I guess I'd answer the question by posing another question and answering it.
What would I like to be remembered for in the next 10 years?
If people summed over my productivity,
from 1987 to 1997, I'd like to be remembered for being the grand architect who put together the School-University Research Collaborative.
I want to work on applied research.
I want to work on communicating and translating research findings for practitioners and policymakers.
I don't want to be a theoretician.
And the School-University Collaborative
provides those opportunities to link the profession as Corden would say.
That's where I am.
This has really been wonderful.
I totally appreciate your time and your insights because they're invaluable.
